        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2013-06-16 16:32:51.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nTests received by maloo, run on el6/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/5dbeb13e-d6a2-11e2-a0c9-52540035b04c).  Ran 1 tests.  1 tests failed: node-provisioning-1.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "d471f66637efb0e3582dc6b3d2b295aa729602a6",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-06-17 15:37:19.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nIs this only true because of GNU fileutils doing stat() on every file before unlinking it, or is this handled entirely during the kernel lookup process?\n\nOtherwise, you are trading some CPU cycles on the client for an extra round trip from the MDS to the client in order to cancel this lock.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "0084a287408011fcdc02b0bc259e59390216ca3f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-06-30 06:21:07.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nAndreas, it is the kernel logic to lookup the target to be unlinked in VFS.\n\nAndrew, what about the rename case? Is it necessary to process the rename src/tgt as unlink does?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "6dc78e8451e92d9ee39d1d387b92227b0168f3b6",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 142
      },
      "date": "2013-07-01 17:41:41.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThe lookup is performed by the kernel doing unlink, and the result of dcache re-lookup in ll_child_get_fid() cannot be different from the argument of unlink/rmdir.\n\nI think, the optimization can be extended on rename as well, but this was not tested.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "d16f52d456c4ff72fbe71640a89f397e2efa115f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 142
      },
      "date": "2013-07-01 17:45:21.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nFan Yong, do you want me to include the rename case in the patch?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "f7fdb533c572f4c43380f573340fb1ca4b6aa59c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-07-02 00:16:15.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> Andrew Perepechko\t\t1:45 AM\n> Patch Set 1:\n> Fan Yong, do you want me to include the rename case in the patch?\n\nYes, I hope the logic to be kept the same, then it is more easy for others to understand. So please change and verify rename cases. Thanks!",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "ee002982f5f7e4d8156e3b953fb69127d9b4c6a6",
      "author": {
